  "signature": "ed25519:9c4e2a1f7b3d5e8c0a6f2b4d7e1c3a5f8b0d2e4c6a8f0b2d4e6c8a0f2b4d6e8c",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used in the analysis (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) must be verified under an FDA-recognized quality management system; all simulation scripts version-controlled in a validated repository; audit trail demonstrating traceability from input deck to output result.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is operated under a 21 CFR Part 11-compliant quality system at DePuy Synthes. All FEA scripts are maintained in a validated Git repository with change-control procedures. FDA and academic collaborators used independently validated solver installations. Gradation 3 is satisfied: QMS documentation, software validation records, and version-controlled scripts are on file."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10.1 must be reproduced within 1% of analytical solutions for linear-elastic beam bending and contact patch problems representative of the screw-rod interface geometry.",
      "rationale": "Standard Ansys verification benchmarks for beam bending and Hertzian contact were executed and documented. All benchmark results fell within 0.4% of analytical solutions, satisfying the Gradation 2 requirement for code verification in this application domain."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A mesh convergence study must demonstrate that QoI values (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) change by less than 2% between the medium and fine mesh densities; Richardson extrapolation must be applied to estimate the discretization error bound.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the screw-rod assembly using element edge lengths of 1.0 mm, 0.5 mm, and 0.25 mm in the critical screw-rod contact region. Richardson extrapolation yielded a discretization error estimate of 0.8% for stiffness and 1.1% for yield force, both within the 2% acceptance bound. The fine mesh (0.25 mm) was adopted for all production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge to below 1e-6 for force and moment equilibrium in all load steps; nonlinear convergence plots must be archived for each simulation run.",
      "rationale": "All production simulations achieved force and moment residuals below 1e-8 within the default Newton-Raphson iteration scheme. Convergence plots are archived in the project repository. No divergence or premature termination was observed across the 11-construct ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "An independent analyst must perform a blind re-run of at least two representative constructs using only the documented input decks; results must agree with primary analyst outputs within 0.5%.",
      "rationale": "An independent FDA analyst reproduced two of the 11 construct simulations using only the archived input decks and solver instructions. Differences in QoI values were 0.2% and 0.3%, confirming that documented procedures are sufficient to eliminate analyst-induced variability. Gradation 3 achieved, exceeding the Gradation 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model selection (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V) must be justified by published coupon-level validation data; contact formulation must be documented and sensitivity-tested against frictionless and fully-bonded extremes.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening parameters for Ti-6Al-4V were drawn from published ASTM coupon test data (E = 114 GPa, yield 880 MPa, tangent modulus 1.2 GPa). Sensitivity analysis spanning frictionless (μ=0) to high-friction (μ=0.3) contact confirmed that QoI predictions vary by less than 3% across the plausible friction range, consistent with the literature. The augmented Lagrange contact formulation was selected for its robustness in large-deformation regimes."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material property distributions must be characterized from lot-specific coupon testing for each construct batch; geometric dimensions must be verified by CMM measurement of at least three screws per lot with tolerances traceable to design drawings.",
      "rationale": "Lot-specific tensile coupon data (n=6 per lot) were used to parameterize the bilinear hardening model for each construct batch. CMM measurements confirmed that screw geometry was within ±0.02 mm of nominal across all 11 constructs. Polyaxial head engagement torque was recorded and mapped to an equivalent contact preload in the model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least 10 experimental constructs must be tested; constructs must span at least two independent build lots; inter-laboratory reproducibility must be confirmed by testing at least one shared construct configuration at both laboratories.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (FDA and a contract test facility), spanning two production lots. One shared construct configuration was tested at both sites, yielding inter-laboratory stiffness agreement within 2.1%, confirming reproducibility. Sample size exceeds the minimum required for statistical comparison per ASME V&V 40 Table 1 at the Medium model risk level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span at least two load levels and two rod diameters representative of the clinical use envelope; environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) must be controlled and recorded throughout each test.",
      "rationale": "All experimental testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 load configuration (compression-bending, 10 mm offset, 5.5 mm rod diameter). While temperature and humidity were controlled and logged throughout, only one load level and one rod diameter were evaluated, limiting coverage of the clinical use envelope. This factor therefore achieves Gradation 2 rather than the required Gradation 3. The gap is acknowledged; the assessment team determined that the single-condition validation remains adequate for the specific COU (non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, standard 5.5 mm rod, compression-bending only) and that the model risk is mitigated by the high agreement observed across all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A traceability matrix must map each experimental measurement (geometry, material, boundary condition) to the corresponding model input parameter, with documented uncertainty propagation for each mapping.",
      "rationale": "A formal traceability matrix was developed linking CMM geometry measurements, coupon material data, and fixture compliance measurements to their model counterparts. Uncertainty in each mapping was propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis (n=1000 samples), confirming that parameter equivalency uncertainty contributes less than 1.5% to total QoI uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Predicted QoI values (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) were compared against experimental means using the validation metric E/uval, where uval incorporates both experimental measurement uncertainty and model prediction uncertainty. All three QoIs returned E/uval values below 1.96 (stiffness: 0.84, yield force: 1.21, force at 40 mm: 1.07), satisfying the pre-specified acceptance criterion. The percentage difference between FEA ensemble mean and experimental mean was 3.2%, 4.7%, and 2.9% for the three QoIs respectively, each well within the 10% bound. Gradation 3 is achieved: a formal uncertainty-aware validation metric was applied, results are within pre-established bounds, and the comparison methodology is fully documented in the validation report. The statistical framework follows FDA guidance on computational modeling and the ASME V&V 40-2018 standard. No post-hoc adjustment of model parameters was performed after the experimental data were unblinded, preserving the integrity of the predictive comparison. Sensitivity of the E/uval metric to the assumed experimental uncertainty budget was tested by varying uexp by ±20%; all QoIs remained within the acceptance region under this perturbation, confirming robustness of the conclusion."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation must be directly traceable to the device performance endpoints specified in the predicate device 510(k) and the ASTM F1717 standard; a clinical relevance justification must be documented for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary endpoints specified in ASTM F1717-15 and are directly cited in the predicate device 510(k). Clinical relevance is established: stiffness governs load sharing with the vertebral column, yield force determines the onset of permanent deformation under physiological loading, and force at 40 mm represents ultimate structural integrity. Each QoI is therefore directly relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario (geometry, loading, boundary conditions, material) must match the COU scenario within documented similarity bounds; any differences must be assessed for their impact on model credibility using a formal similarity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU scenario: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same ASTM F1717 test fixture, and the same loading protocol are used in both the validation experiments and the intended regulatory submission analysis. A formal similarity analysis confirmed that no extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the COU. Gradation 3 is satisfied."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors were assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors met or exceeded their required gradation levels. One factor (Test conditions) achieved Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 due to the single-condition experimental program; the assessment team determined this shortfall is acceptable given the narrow and well-defined COU, the high agreement observed across all three QoIs (E/uval < 1.96 for all), and the absence of any clinical scenario requiring extrapolation beyond the validated load configuration. The overall credibility assessment supports an Accepted decision at the Medium assurance level for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
